    "reasoning": "For Problem 1, three faces of a unit cube sharing a vertex are projected onto a plane. Their areas x, y, z are proportional to 6:10:15. Since the areas equal the absolute values of the components of the unit normal vector to the plane, we have x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 1. Setting x = 6k, y = 10k, z = 15k gives (36 + 100 + 225)k^2 = 361k^2 = 1, so k = 1/19. Thus z = 15/19. The required value is k = z + 23/19 = 15/19 + 23/19 = 38/19 = 2. For Problem 2, Bill has n cents and can buy packages costing 6 cents (7 pencils) or 10 cents (12 pencils). We need the smallest n such that there is a combination spending exactly n cents yielding P pencils, and a combination spending exactly n+2 cents yielding fewer than P pencils. Let n = 2k, so 3a + 5b = k and P = (7k + b)/3. The condition is equivalent to min P(n+2) < max P(n), which reduces to b_max(k) - b_min(k+1) > 7, where b_max is the largest b admissible for k and b_min is the smallest for k+1. Checking k values, the smallest satisfying this is k = 50 (n = 100). For n = 100, one combination gives 120 pencils; for n+2 = 102, a combination gives 119 pencils, which is fewer. Thus the smallest n is 100.",
